# Investigation 002 — Wireshark PCAP Traffic Analysis

Date: 18/05/2026  
Analyst:Sadiq Ssali Abdulaziz  
Tool Used:Wireshark  
Data Source: PCAP file — 2014-11-08 traffic analysis exercise  
Source: malware-traffic-analysis.net  

 Overview
Analysed a packet capture file containing 10,205 packets 
to identify malicious network activity and reconstruct 
an attack chain.

 Protocol Breakdown
| Protocol | Percentage |
|----------|------------|
| Ethernet | 100% |
| IPv4 | 100% |
| TCP | 96% |
| UDP | 3.1% |
| HTTP | 5.5% |
 Suspicious Domains Identified
| Domain | Requests | Verdict |
|--------|----------|---------|
| seedradrivergy.co.vu | 9 | 🚨 Malicious — redirect to exploit |
| genfaglobal.ga | 1 | 🚨 Malicious — exploit delivery |
| kentroxarisma.com | 36 | 🚨 Compromised WordPress site |
| retrocollect.com | 109 | ✅ Legitimate |
| theastrologyroom.com | 82 | ✅ Legitimate |


Victim Machine Details
- IP Address: 172.16.165.133
- Operating System: Windows 7
- Browser: Internet Explorer 8 (outdated, vulnerable)
- Time of infection:2014-11-08 around 21:25 UTC

 Key Evidence Found
- HTTP 302 redirect from seedradrivergy.co.vu 
  to malicious URL containing random hash string
- Referer header showing victim came from Bing search
- kentroxarisma.com running vulnerable WordPress 
  with xmlrpc.php exposed
- genfaglobal.ga serving lissyanger17.html exploit page
- All malicious requests made by IE8 on Windows 7

 Attack Type
-Drive-by Download via Exploit Kit
Attackers compromised a legitimate WordPress site and 
injected hidden redirect code. Victims visiting the site 
were silently redirected through a chain of malicious 
domains until an exploit was delivered targeting the 
victim's outdated Internet Explorer 8 browser.

#Wireshark Filters Used
http
http.host contains "seedradrivergy"
http contains "genfaglobal"
http contains "kentroxarisma"
http.request.method == "GET"


 #Recommendations
- Never use Internet Explorer 8 — it is end of life 
  and full of unpatched vulnerabilities
- Keep browsers updated at all times
- Use web filtering to block suspicious TLDs like 
  .ga .vu .tk .pw
- WordPress sites should be regularly updated and 
  monitored for malicious injections

#What I Learned
- How to use Statistics → Protocol Hierarchy in Wireshark
- How to use Statistics → HTTP → Requests to find domains
- How to follow TCP streams to read full conversations
- What a drive-by download exploit kit attack looks like
- How to identify compromised WordPress sites in traffic
- How HTTP 302 redirects are used in malware chains
- Importance of keeping browsers updated
